attachments.title: Galvanize - Web Development Resident (WDR)
attachments.text: THIS POSITION IS RESERVED FOR FORMER STUDENTS AND GRADUATES OF GALVANIZE IMMERSIVE PROGRAMSBeing a Web Developer-in-Residence (WDR), you would be here at Galvanize Full Time (40 hours per week). The idea is to solidify your new skills through helping students in the classroom as well as going through the curriculum again. In addition, you'd have a chance to really build out your passion project in the intensely creative and talented eco-system here at Galvanize! Your classroom responsibilities will mostly include ‘being on the floor’ which means helping students through the daily exercises. Other classroom responsibilities include reviewing new student applications, interviewing prospective students, building new / iterating current curriculum, grading student tests, and reviewing student code. Your off-time can be devoted to your personal project(s) is designed to give you time to solidify your full stack developer skills, explore passion projects, ramp up your portfolio, and contribute to the Galvanize learning experience in a positive way. As part of the Residency program, you will receive dedicated mentorship from our expert instructors and faculty to cultivate your development as a web developer. It is a 12-week appointment. There is a possible extension an additional 12 weeks depending on staffing needs. WDR contracts will work with Solo Weeks, which will include helping students with their personal and capstone projects as needed. WDRs will be compensated for these weeks as part of the 12-week appointment. San Francisco & Seattle Rates: For 40-hours of work/ week, the stipend is approximately $1,500/ week for 12- week appointment. **(Approximate because stipend depending on actual days worked.) Austin & Colorado Rates: For 40-hours of work/ week, the stipend is approximately $1,250/ week for 12-week appointment. **(Approximate because stipend depending on actual days worked.) We are looking for 1 Resident per cohort depending on staffing needs.

attachments.text: Six Degrees of Kevin Bacon is a parlour game based on the "six degrees of separation" concept, which posits that any two people on Earth are six or fewer acquaintance links apart. Movie buffs challenge each other to find the shortest path between an arbitrary actor and prolific character actor Kevin Bacon. It rests on the assumption that anyone involved in the Hollywood film industry can be linked through their film roles to Bacon within six steps. The game requires a group of players to try to connect any such individual to Kevin Bacon as quickly as possible and in as few links as possible. In 2007, Bacon started a charitable organization named <http://SixDegrees.org|SixDegrees.org>.

attachments.title: Google launches final release version of Angular 2.0
attachments.text:
After&nbsp;Google launched the first version of its Angular web application framework in 2010, it quickly became one of the hottest web technologies. Since then, the web has changed, though, and when Google announced Angular 2&nbsp;in 2014, it created quite a stir in the web development community because this new version wasn&rsquo;t just an update, but instead a complete rewrite that wasn&rsquo;t compatible with the older version. Today, after numerous preview and beta releases, the company is officially launching the final release version of Angular 2.0.
&ldquo;Angular 1 first solved the problem of how to develop for an emerging web,&rdquo; the company writes in today&rsquo;s announcement. &ldquo;Six years later, the challenges faced by today&rsquo;s application developers, and the sophistication of the devices that applications must support, have both changed immensely.&rdquo;
Application developers today, however, also have a far wider choice of JavaScript frameworks. Facebook&rsquo;s React framework especially has a lot of momentum behind it, though, to be fair, the two projects have slightly different styles (Angular is a far more opinionated framework, for example) and strengths (React Native makes it easy to build native apps, for example). But given that Google doesn&rsquo;t give developers who built applications with Angular&nbsp;1.x an easy upgrade path, many of them are now looking at which technology to use next.
Angular 2.0 introduces a number of new features, including better support for modern browsers and mobile development. The team also moved a lot of the core functionality into modules that now make it easier to use third-party libraries in addition to the built-in ones.&nbsp;The team now also recommends that developers use TypeScript to write their apps. TypeScript is a Microsoft-developed superset&nbsp;of JavaScript that adds features like static typing and class-based object-oriented programming.
Looking ahead, the Angular team&nbsp;plans to provide developers with more guides and examples to help them learn Angular 2.0 faster. In addition, the team plans to put more work into animations for Angular 2.0 and move its WebWorker support out of its experimental branch. Angular Universal, a project that lets you render your app server-side so first-time users will quickly see a server-rendered version of your site, for example, will also soon get support for more languages.
Going forward, the team will also move to releasing Angular updates through three channels (major, minor and patch). Major versions are those that introduce incompatible API changes. Minor versions signal the addition of backwards-compatible functionality and&nbsp;the version numbers for the patch version ticks up as backwards-compatible bugs are fixed.
